    ## Hybrid Approaches with Precomputed Data
    
    One effective method uses a large stored data table to get close to the right answer first, then finishes with a relatively short computation. The program adds up bin counts until the sum exceeds n to determine which bin the nth prime falls into, then the prime can be found using a sieve algorithm on that bin.
    
    ## Computational Complexity
    
    For finding the nth prime without generating all preceding primes, the practical complexity is O(n^(2/3) / log²n), which is much more efficient than standard sieve approaches.
    
    ## Modern High-Performance Methods
    
    The nth prime can be done using fast prime counting methods so the 10^12th prime can be exactly determined in under a second. These methods employ prime counting functions (like π(x)) rather than generating all primes sequentially.
    
    ## Sieve-Based Techniques
    
    The Sieve of Eratosthenes has time complexity O(n log log n) operations. The page segmented version has the same operational complexity but reduces space requirements to the minimal size of the segment page plus memory for base primes.
    
    The search results focus on well-established algorithmic approaches rather than recent 2025-2026 developments, as this is a relatively mature research area where fundamental techniques have remained consistent in recent years.
    
    
