    ## Compressed Sensing and Sparse Recovery (2025-2026)
    
    Sparse signal recovery is a key problem in compressive sensing, with the restricted isometry property (RIP) serving as an important metric for the recoverability of sparse signals.
    
    Recent developments include:
    
    - A new metric called the combinatorial condition number has been defined to overcome drawbacks of RIP, as it is invariant for scalar rescaling.
    
    - Theory-based algorithms have been proposed to identify and correct destructive weights in weighted ℓ1 minimization schemes through a novel sparsity-inducing property (SIP) which establishes a necessary condition for successful signal recovery.
    
    - Compressive sensing is a transformative signal processing framework that enables sparse signal acquisition at rates below the Nyquist limit, with substantial advantages in data efficiency and reconstruction accuracy.
    
