    ## Overview of PSLQ Algorithm
    
    The PSLQ algorithm was developed by Ferguson and Bailey in 1992 and substantially simplified by Ferguson, Bailey, and Arno in 1999. In 2000 the PSLQ algorithm was selected as one of the "Top Ten Algorithms of the Century" by Jack Dongarra and Francis Sullivan.
    
    ## Applications to Automated Conjecture Discovery
    
    A typical approach in experimental mathematics is to use numerical methods and arbitrary precision arithmetic to find an approximate value for an infinite series, infinite product or an integral to a high degree of precision, and then use an integer relation algorithm to search for an integer relation between this value and a set of mathematical constants. If an integer relation is found, this suggests a possible closed-form expression for the original series, product or integral. This conjecture can then be validated by formal algebraic methods.
    
    ## Recent 2025 Research
    
    The search results include a recent 2025 paper (published at ICLR 2025) on automated discovery using PSLQ. The numerical nature of their algorithms means that results are not theorems, but rather conjectures awaiting proofs. In many cases, the discovered relations between formulas led to patterns that enabled generalizing formulas into families.
    
    Regarding prime numbers specifically, the search results don't contain direct information connecting PSLQ to prime number formulas in 2025, but the algorithm is a fundamental tool for discovering mathematical relationships that could apply to various mathematical constants and sequences.
    
    
